Chapter 2: Build the Society Archive
Core Question
Where does the society’s memory live?
Understand
A society without memory must keep beginning again.
The archive protects memory.
The archive should not be a messy folder where documents disappear. It should be a simple, organized place where the society can find its decisions, reports, rules, meetings, financial summaries, project records, and learning.
The archive is not nostalgia.
It is infrastructure.
The archive should include:
Purpose
 Covenant
 Rules
 Meeting notes
 Treasury summaries
 Ledger exports or snapshots
 Aid summaries
 Care team reports
 Needs Map updates
 Skills and Assets Map
 First Action record
 Day 100 Report
 Next Container Report
 Role descriptions
 Training notes
 Important decisions
 Conflict resolutions where appropriate
 History lessons used
 Decolonization reflections if shareable
 Photos or media with consent
A good archive makes succession possible.
A new recordkeeper should be able to understand the society without guessing.
Discuss
Where are our records now?
What is missing?
Who can access what?
What should be private?
What should be public?
What should be archived after every meeting?
Build: Archive Structure
Create folders or sections:
[ ] 01 Purpose and Covenant
 [ ] 02 Members and Roles
