Chapter 3: Turn Habits Into Procedures
Core Question
What do we need to make repeatable?
Understand
A habit becomes institutional when it can be repeated by someone else.
If only one person knows how to prepare the meeting, update the ledger, approve aid, send the report, or coordinate care, the society is fragile.
Procedures do not need to be long.
They need to be clear.
A simple procedure answers:
When does this happen?
 Who does it?
 What steps do they follow?
 What records are created?
 Who reviews it?
 What happens if something goes wrong?
Procedures protect the society from confusion and personality-dependence.
They also make training easier.
Discuss
What do we do repeatedly?
Which repeated tasks are unclear?
Where do people keep asking the same questions?
What process depends too much on one person?
What procedure would reduce confusion immediately?
