PART TWO: STANDARDIZE GOVERNANCE

Chapter 4: Clarify Decision-Making
Core Question
How do we make decisions without confusion or domination?
Understand
An institution must know how decisions are made.
Without a decision process, decisions happen through personality, urgency, popularity, private conversations, or exhaustion.
Decision-making should be clear before pressure arrives.
Different decisions may require different processes.
For example:
Small care team decision
 Treasury expense
 Aid approval
 Rule change
 New member approval
 Business campaign
 Property project
 Public statement
 Partnership
 Legal or financial commitment
Not every decision needs a full vote.
Not every decision should be made by one person.
The society needs a decision map.
Discuss
Which decisions can be made by role leads?
Which decisions require governance?
Which decisions require member input?
Which decisions require two-person approval?
Which decisions should be delayed for reflection?
What decisions should never be made privately?
