PART FOUR: PROTECT THE INSTITUTION

Chapter 10: Protect Money, Privacy, and Records
Core Question
What must be protected as the society grows?
Understand
Growth increases risk.
More people means more access.
More money means more scrutiny.
More needs mean more sensitive information.
More projects mean more records.
The society must protect:
Money
 Ledger
 Bank or payment access
 Aid details
 Member information
 Youth information
 Elder vulnerability
 Property details
 Reflection responses
 Meeting notes
 Conflicts
 Reports
 Passwords or admin access
 Public reputation
Protection is not distrust.
Protection makes trust possible.
Discuss
What information is most sensitive?
Who currently has access?
Who should have access?
What access should be removed?
What should never appear in public reports?
What protection rule is missing?
