What can now outlive the people who started it?

Closing Principle
A society becomes an institution when the work no longer depends on one person’s memory, charisma, urgency, or sacrifice.
It becomes an institution when care has structure.
When money has records.
When meetings have decisions.
When conflict has repair.
When roles have backups.
When leadership has training.
When memory has an archive.
When growth has standards.
When the future has a plan.
This is the work that makes the work last.
Build what can outlive you.

